[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] In computing, a **Monte Carlo algorithm** is a randomized algorithm whose output may be incorrect with a certain (typically small) probability.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Two examples of such algorithms are the Karger–Stein algorithm and the Monte Carlo algorithm for minimum feedback arc set.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] The name refers to the Monte Carlo casino in the Principality of Monaco, which is well-known around the world as an icon of gambling.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] The term "Monte Carlo" was first introduced in 1947 by Nicholas Metropolis.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms are a dual of Monte Carlo algorithms and never return an incorrect answer.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] However, they may make random choices as part of their work.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] As a result, the time taken might vary between runs, even with the same input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] If there is a procedure for verifying whether the answer given by a Monte Carlo algorithm is correct, and the probability of a correct answer is bounded above zero, then with probability one, running the algorithm repeatedly while testing the answers will eventually give a correct answer.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Whether this process is a Las Vegas algorithm depends on whether halting with probability one is considered to satisfy the definition.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] While the answer returned by a deterministic algorithm is always expected to be correct, this is not the case for Monte Carlo algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] For decision problems, these algorithms are generally classified as either **false**-biased or **true**-biased.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] A **false**-biased Monte Carlo algorithm is always correct when it returns **false**; a **true**-biased algorithm is always correct when it returns **true**.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] While this describes algorithms with *one-sided errors*, others might have no bias; these are said to have *two-sided errors*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] The answer they provide (either **true** or **false**) will be incorrect, or correct, with some bounded probability.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] For instance, the Solovay–Strassen primality test is used to determine whether a given number is a prime number.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] It always answers **true** for prime number inputs; for composite inputs, it answers **false** with probability at least 1⁄2 and **true** with probability less than 1⁄2.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Thus, **false** answers from the algorithm are certain to be correct, whereas the **true** answers remain uncertain; this is said to be a *1⁄2-correct false-biased algorithm*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] For a Monte Carlo algorithm with one-sided errors, the failure probability can be reduced (and the success probability amplified) by running the algorithm *k* times.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Consider again the Solovay–Strassen algorithm which is *1⁄2-correct false-biased*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] One may run this algorithm multiple times returning a **false** answer if it reaches a **false** response within *k* iterations, and otherwise returning **true**.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Thus, if the number is prime then the answer is always correct, and if the number is composite then the answer is correct with probability at least 1−(1−1⁄2)*k* = 1−2*−k*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] For Monte Carlo decision algorithms with two-sided error, the failure probability may again be reduced by running the algorithm *k* times and returning the majority function of the answers.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] In contrast, the complexity class ZPP describes problems solvable by polynomial expected time Las Vegas algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] ZPP ⊆ RP ⊆ BPP, but it is not known whether any of these complexity classes is distinct from each other; that is, Monte Carlo algorithms may have more computational power than Las Vegas algorithms, but this has not been proven.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Another complexity class, PP, describes decision problems with a polynomial-time Monte Carlo algorithm that is more accurate than flipping a coin but where the error probability cannot necessarily be bounded away from 1⁄2.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are primarily divided by its two main types, Monte Carlo and Las Vegas, however, these represent only a top of the hierarchy and can be further categorized.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Previous table represents a general framework for Monte Carlo and Las Vegas randomized algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Instead of the mathematical symbol < one could use $\leq$ , thus making probabilities in the worst case equal.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/monte-carlo-algorithm] Well-known Monte Carlo algorithms include the Solovay–Strassen primality test, the Baillie–PSW primality test, the Miller–Rabin primality test, and certain fast variants of the Schreier–Sims algorithm in computational group theory.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] In mathematics, the **probabilistic method** is a nonconstructive method, primarily used in combinatorics and pioneered by Paul Erdős, for proving the existence of a prescribed kind of mathematical object.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] It works by showing that if one randomly chooses objects from a specified class, the probability that the result is of the prescribed kind is strictly greater than zero.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Although the proof uses probability, the final conclusion is determined for certain, without any possible error.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] This method has now been applied to other areas of mathematics such as number theory, linear algebra, and real analysis, as well as in computer science (e.g. randomized rounding) and information theory.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] If every object in a collection of objects fails to have a certain property, then the probability that a random object chosen from the collection has that property is zero.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Thus, by contraposition, if the probability that a random object chosen from the collection has that property is nonzero, then some object in the collection must possess the property.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Similarly, showing that the probability is (strictly) less than 1 can be used to prove the existence of an object that does *not* satisfy the prescribed properties.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Another way to use the probabilistic method is by calculating the expected value of some random variable.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] If it can be shown that the random variable can take on a value less than the expected value, this proves that the random variable can also take on some value greater than the expected value.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Common tools used in the probabilistic method include Markov's inequality, the Chernoff bound, and the Lovász local lemma.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Although others before him proved theorems via the probabilistic method (for example, Szele's 1943 result that there exist tournaments containing a large number of Hamiltonian cycles), many of the most well known proofs using this method are due to Erdős.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] The first example below describes one such result from 1947 that gives a proof of a lower bound for the Ramsey number $R(r,r)$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Suppose we have a complete graph on n vertices.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] We wish to show (for small enough values of n ) that it is possible to color the edges of the graph in two colors (say red and blue) so that there is no complete subgraph on r vertices which is monochromatic (every edge colored the same color).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Color each edge independently with probability $1/2$ of being red and $1/2$ of being blue.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] For any set $S_{r}$ of r vertices from our graph, define the variable $X(S_{r})$ to be 1 if every edge amongst the r vertices is the same color, and 0 otherwise.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Note that the number of monochromatic r -subgraphs is the sum of $X(S_{r})$ over all possible subsets $S_{r}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] (the factor of 2 comes because there are two possible colors).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] This holds true for any of the $C(n,r)$ possible subsets we could have chosen, i.e. i ranges from 1 to $C(n,r)$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Consider what happens if this value is less than 1 .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Since the expected number of monochromatic r -subgraphs is strictly less than 1 , there exists a coloring satisfying the condition that the number of monochromatic r -subgraphs is strictly less than 1 .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] The number of monochromatic r -subgraphs in this random coloring is a non-negative integer, hence it must be 0 ( 0 is the only non-negative integer less than 1 ).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] (which holds, for example, for $n=5$ and $r=4$ ), there must exist a coloring in which there are no monochromatic r -subgraphs.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] By definition of the Ramsey number, this implies that $R(r,r)$ must be bigger than n .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] In particular, $R(r,r)$ must grow at least exponentially with r .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] A weakness of this argument is that it is entirely nonconstructive.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] The problem of finding such a coloring has been open for more than 50 years.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] A 1959 paper of Erdős (see reference cited below) addressed the following problem in graph theory: given positive integers g and k, does there exist a graph G containing only cycles of length at least g, such that the chromatic number of G is at least k?
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] It can be shown that such a graph exists for any g and k, and the proof is reasonably simple.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Let n be very large and consider a random graph G on n vertices, where every edge in G exists with probability *p* = *n*1/*g*−1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] and each of them is present in G with probability *pi*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] For sufficiently large n, the probability that a graph from the distribution has both properties is positive, as the events for these properties cannot be disjoint (if they were, their probabilities would sum up to more than 1).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] Here comes the trick: since G has these two properties, we can remove at most *n*/2 vertices from G to obtain a new graph *G′* on $n'\geq n/2$ vertices that contains only cycles of length at least g.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] We can see that this new graph has no independent set of size $\left\lceil {\frac {n'}{k}}\right\rceil$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] *G′* can only be partitioned into at least k independent sets, and, hence, has chromatic number at least k.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/probabilistic-method] This result gives a hint as to why the computation of the chromatic number of a graph is so difficult: even when there are no local reasons (such as small cycles) for a graph to require many colors the chromatic number can still be arbitrarily large.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] If for a function *f* evaluating any instance *x* can be reduced in polynomial time to the evaluation of *f* on one or more random instances *yi*, then it is self-reducible (this is also known as a *non-adaptive uniform self-reduction*).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] In a random self-reduction, an arbitrary worst-case instance *x* in the domain of *f* is mapped to a random set of instances *y*1, ..., *yk*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] This is done so that *f*(*x*) can be computed in polynomial time, given the coin-toss sequence from the mapping, *x*, and *f*(*y*1), ..., *f*(*yk*).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Therefore, taking the average with respect to the induced distribution on *yi*, the average-case complexity of *f* is the same (within polynomial factors) as the worst-case randomized complexity of *f*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] One special case of note is when each random instance *yi* is distributed uniformly over the entire set of elements in the domain of *f* that have a length of |*x*|.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] In this case *f* is as hard on average as it is in the worst case.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] This approach contains two key restrictions.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] First the generation of *y*1, ..., *yk* is performed non-adaptively.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] This means that *y*2 is picked before *f*(*y*1) is known.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Second, it is not necessary that the points *y*1, ..., *yk* be uniformly distributed.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Problems that require some privacy in the data (typically *cryptographic problems*) can use randomization to ensure that privacy.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] In fact, the only provably secure cryptographic system (the one-time pad) has its security relying totally on the *randomness* of the key data supplied to the system.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] The field of cryptography utilizes the fact that certain number-theoretic functions are randomly self-reducible.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] This includes probabilistic encryption and cryptographically strong pseudorandom number generation.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Also, instance-hiding schemes (where a weak private device uses a strong public device without revealing its data) are easily exemplified by random self-reductions.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] The discrete logarithm problem, the quadratic residuosity problem, the RSA inversion problem, and the problem of computing the permanent of a matrix are each random self-reducible problems.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Take *B* to be distributed uniformly on {0,...,|*G*| − 1}, then *xg**B* = *g**k*+*B* is also distributed uniformly on *G*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Therefore *xg**B* is independent of *x*, and its logarithm can be computed with probability 1/poly(*n*) in polynomial time.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Then logg*x* ≡ log*g**xg**B* - *B* (mod |*G*|) and the discrete logarithm is self-reducible.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Given the definition of the permanent of a matrix, it is clear that *PERM*(*M*) for any *n*-by-*n* matrix *M* is a multivariate polynomial of degree *n* over the entries in *M*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Calculating the permanent of a matrix is a difficult computational task—*PERM* has been shown to be #P-complete (proof).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Moreover, the ability to compute *PERM*(*M*) for most matrices implies the existence of a random program that computes *PERM*(*M*) for all matrices.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] This demonstrates that *PERM* is random self-reducible.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] The discussion below considers the case where the matrix entries are drawn from a finite field *Fp* for some prime *p*, and where all arithmetic is performed in that field.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Let *X* be a random *n*-by-*n* matrix with entries from *Fp*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Since all the entries of any matrix *M* + *kX* are linear functions of *k*, by composing those linear functions with the degree *n* multivariate polynomial that calculates *PERM*(*M*) we get another degree *n* polynomial on *k*, which we will call *p*(*k*).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Clearly, *p*(0) is equal to the permanent of *M*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Suppose we know a program that computes the correct value of *PERM*(*A*) for most *n*-by-*n* matrices with entries from *Fp*---specifically, 1 − 1/(3*n*) of them.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Then with probability of approximately two-thirds, we can calculate *PERM*(*M* + *kX*) for *k* = 1,2,...,*n* + 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Once we have those *n* + 1 values, we can solve for the coefficients of *p*(*k*) using interpolation (remember that *p*(*k*) has degree *n*).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] Once we know *p*(*k*) exactly, we evaluate *p*(0), which is equal to *PERM*(*M*).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/random-self-reducibility] If we do so, we run the risk of being wrong 1/3 of the time, but by picking multiple random *X*s and repeating the above procedure many times, and only providing the majority winner as an answer, we can drive the error rate down very low.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
