[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In computer science and operations research, **randomized rounding** is a widely used approach for designing and analyzing approximation algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Many combinatorial optimization problems are computationally intractable to solve exactly (to optimality).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] For such problems, randomized rounding can be used to design fast (polynomial time) approximation algorithms—that is, algorithms that are guaranteed to return an approximately optimal solution given any input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The basic idea of randomized rounding is to convert an optimal solution of a relaxation of the problem into an approximately-optimal solution to the original problem.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The resulting algorithm is usually analyzed using the probabilistic method.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Compute an optimal fractional solution x to the linear programming relaxation (LP) of the ILP.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Round the fractional solution x of the LP to an integer solution $x'$ of the ILP.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] (Although the approach is most commonly applied with linear programs, other kinds of relaxations are sometimes used.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In the first step, the challenge is to choose a suitable integer linear program.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Familiarity with linear programming, in particular modelling using linear programs and integer linear programs, is required.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] For many problems, there is a natural integer linear program that works well, such as in the Set Cover example below.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In the second step, the optimal fractional solution can typically be computed in polynomial time using any standard linear programming algorithm.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In the third step, the fractional solution must be converted into an integer solution (and thus a solution to the original problem).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] This is called *rounding* the fractional solution.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The resulting integer solution should (provably) have cost not much larger than the cost of the fractional solution.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] This will ensure that the cost of the integer solution is not much larger than the cost of the optimal integer solution.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The main technique used to do the third step (rounding) is to use randomization, and then to use probabilistic arguments to bound the increase in cost due to the rounding (following the probabilistic method from combinatorics).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Therein, probabilistic arguments are used to show the existence of discrete structures with desired properties.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Finally, to make the third step computationally efficient, one either shows that $x'$ approximates x with high probability (so that the step can remain randomized) or one derandomizes the rounding step, typically using the method of conditional probabilities.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The latter method converts the randomized rounding process into an efficient deterministic process that is guaranteed to reach a good outcome.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The following example illustrates how randomized rounding can be used to design an approximation algorithm for the set cover problem.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Fix any instance $\langle c,{\mathcal {S}}\rangle$ of set cover over a universe ${\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] For **step 1**, let IP be the standard integer linear program for set cover for this instance.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] For **step 2**, let LP be the linear programming relaxation of IP, and compute an optimal solution $x^{*}$ to LP using any standard linear programming algorithm.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] This takes time polynomial in the input size.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Note that any set cover ${\mathcal {C}}$ for ${\mathcal {S}}$ gives a feasible solution x (where $x_{s}=1$ for $s\in {\mathcal {C}}$ , $x_{s}=0$ otherwise).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In other words, the linear program LP is a relaxation of the given set-cover problem.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Since $x^{*}$ has minimum cost among feasible solutions to the LP, *the cost of $x^{*}$ is a lower bound on the cost of the optimal set cover*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In **step 3**, we must convert the minimum-cost fractional set cover $x^{*}$ into a feasible integer solution $x'$ (corresponding to a true set cover).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The rounding step should produce an $x'$ that, with positive probability, has cost within a small factor of the cost of $x^{*}$ .Then (since the cost of $x^{*}$ is a lower bound on the cost of the optimal set cover), the cost of $x'$ will be within a small factor of the optimal cost.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] With this rounding scheme, the expected cost of the chosen sets is at most $\sum _{s}c(s)x_{s}^{*}$ , the cost of the fractional cover.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] So only a constant fraction of the elements will be covered in expectation.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] To make $x'$ cover every element with high probability, the standard rounding scheme first *scales up* the rounding probabilities by an appropriate factor $\lambda >1$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Scaling the probabilities up by $\lambda$ increases the expected cost by $\lambda$ , but makes coverage of all elements likely.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The idea is to choose $\lambda$ as small as possible so that all elements are provably covered with non-zero probability.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] times the cost of the optimal set cover).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] 2. for some element e , $x'$ fails to cover e .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The expectation of each $x'_{s}$ is at most $\lambda x_{s}^{*}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] By linearity of expectation, the expectation of $c\cdot x'$ is at most $\sum _{s}c(s)\lambda x_{s}^{*}=\lambda c\cdot x^{*}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, by Markov's inequality, the probability of the first bad event above is at most $1/2$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, for each of the $|{\mathcal {U}}|$ elements, the probability that the element is not covered is less than $1/(2{\mathcal {U}})$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] By the union bound, the probability that one of the $1+|{\mathcal {U}}|$ bad events happens is less than $1/2+|{\mathcal {U}}|/(2{\mathcal {U}})=1$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, with positive probability there are no bad events and $x'$ is a set cover of cost at most $2\lambda c\cdot x^{*}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The lemma above shows the *existence* of a set cover of cost $O(\log(|{\mathcal {U}}|)c\cdot x^{*}$ ).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In this context our goal is an efficient approximation algorithm, not just an existence proof, so we are not done.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] One approach would be to increase $\lambda$ a little bit, then show that the probability of success is at least, say, 1/4.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] With this modification, repeating the random rounding step a few times is enough to ensure a successful outcome with high probability.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] That approach weakens the approximation ratio.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] We next describe a different approach that yields a deterministic algorithm that is guaranteed to match the approximation ratio of the existence proof above.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The approach is called the method of conditional probabilities.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The deterministic algorithm emulates the randomized rounding scheme: it considers each set $s\in {\mathcal {S}}$ in turn, and chooses $x'_{s}\in \{0,1\}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] But instead of making each choice *randomly* based on $x^{*}$ , it makes the choice *deterministically*, so as to *keep the conditional probability of failure, given the choices so far, below 1*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] We want to be able to set each variable $x'_{s}$ in turn so as to keep the conditional probability of failure below 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] To do this, we need a good bound on the conditional probability of failure.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The bound will come by refining the original existence proof.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] is the set of elements left uncovered at the end.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The random variable F may appear a bit mysterious, but it mirrors the probabilistic proof in a systematic way.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The first term in F comes from applying Markov's inequality to bound the probability of the first bad event (the cost is too high).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] It contributes at least 1 to F if the cost of $x'$ is too high.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The second term counts the number of bad events of the second kind (uncovered elements).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] It contributes at least 1 to F if $x'$ leaves any element uncovered.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, in any outcome where F is less than 1, $x'$ must cover all the elements and have cost meeting the desired bound from the lemma.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In short, if the rounding step fails, then $F\geq 1$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] This implies (by Markov's inequality) that *$E[F]$ is an upper bound on the probability of failure.* Note that the argument above is implicit already in the proof of the lemma, which also shows by calculation that $E[F]<1$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] To apply the method of conditional probabilities, we need to extend the argument to bound the *conditional* probability of failure as the rounding step proceeds.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Usually, this can be done in a systematic way, although it can be technically tedious.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] So, what about the *conditional* probability of failure as the rounding step iterates through the sets?
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Since $F\geq 1$ in any outcome where the rounding step fails, by Markov's inequality, the *conditional* probability of failure is at most the *conditional* expectation of F .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Next we calculate the conditional expectation of F , much as we calculated the unconditioned expectation of F in the original proof.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Consider the state of the rounding process at the end of some iteration t .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Let $S^{(t)}$ denote the sets considered so far (the first t sets in ${\mathcal {S}}$ ).
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] For each set $s\not \in S^{(t)}$ , let $p_{s}=\min(\lambda x_{s}^{*},1)$ denote the probability with which $x'_{s}$ will be set to 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Let ${\mathcal {U}}^{(t)}$ contain the not-yet-covered elements.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Note that $E[F|x^{(t)}]$ is determined only after iteration t .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] To keep the conditional probability of failure below 1, it suffices to keep the conditional expectation of F below 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] To do this, it suffices to keep the conditional expectation of F from increasing.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In the t th iteration, how can the algorithm set $x'_{s'}$ to ensure that $E[F|x^{(t)}]\leq E[F|S^{(t-1)}]$ ?
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] It turns out that it can simply set $x'_{s'}$ so as to *minimize* the resulting value of $E[F|x^{(t)}]$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] To see why, focus on the point in time when iteration t starts.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] At that time, $E[F|x^{(t-1)}]$ is determined, but $E[F|x^{(t)}]$ is not yet determined --- it can take two possible values depending on how $x'_{s'}$ is set in iteration t .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, the algorithm should set $x'_{s'}$ to 0 if this expression is positive, and 1 otherwise.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] times the minimum cost of any (fractional) set cover.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The algorithm ensures that the conditional expectation of F , $E[F\,|\,x^{(t)}]$ , does not increase at each iteration.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Since this conditional expectation is initially less than 1 (as shown previously), the algorithm ensures that the conditional expectation stays below 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Since the conditional probability of failure is at most the conditional expectation of F , in this way the algorithm ensures that the conditional probability of failure stays below 1.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, at the end, when all choices are determined, the algorithm reaches a successful outcome.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] That is, the algorithm above returns a set cover $x'$ of cost at most $2\ln(2|{\mathcal {U}}|)$ times the minimum cost of any (fractional) set cover.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In the example above, the algorithm was guided by the conditional expectation of a random variable F .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In some cases, instead of an exact conditional expectation, an *upper bound* (or sometimes a lower bound) on some conditional expectation is used instead.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] The probability distribution underlying the random experiment is a function of the solution x of a relaxation of the problem instance.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] This fact is crucial to proving the performance guarantee of the approximation algorithm --- that is, that for any problem instance, the algorithm returns a solution that approximates the *optimal solution for that specific instance*.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] In comparison, applications of the probabilistic method in combinatorics typically show the existence of structures whose features depend on other parameters of the input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] For example, consider Turán's theorem, which can be stated as "any graph with n vertices of average degree d must have an independent set of size at least $n/(d+1)$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] (See this for a probabilistic proof of Turán's theorem.) While there are graphs for which this bound is tight, there are also graphs which have independent sets much larger than $n/(d+1)$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/randomized-rounding] Thus, the size of the independent set shown to exist by Turán's theorem in a graph may, in general, be much smaller than the maximum independent set for that graph.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In computational complexity theory, **Yao's principle** (also called **Yao's minimax principle** or **Yao's lemma**) relates the performance of randomized algorithms to deterministic (non-random) algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle is often used to prove limitations on the performance of randomized algorithms, by finding a probability distribution on inputs that is difficult for deterministic algorithms, and inferring that randomized algorithms have the same limitation on their worst case performance.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] This principle is named after Andrew Yao, who first proposed it in a 1977 paper.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] It is closely related to the minimax theorem in the theory of zero-sum games, and to the duality theory of linear programs.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle is formulated in terms of an arbitrary real valued cost measure $c(A,x)$ of an algorithm A on an input x , such as its running time, for which one wishes to study the expected value over randomized algorithms and random inputs.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The algorithms used in this cost measure are drawn from a finite set ${\mathcal {A}}$ of deterministic algorithms; a typical way to make a problem have only a finite set of algorithms is to restrict its inputs to a single size.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The inputs, too, should be drawn from a finite set ${\mathcal {X}}$ , which can be made finite in the same way.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Finally, the formulation of Yao's principle involves the class of all probability distributions on inputs in ${\mathcal {X}}$ , denoted as ${\mathcal {D}}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Here, $\mathbb {E}$ is notation for the expected value, and $x\sim D$ means that x is a random variable distributed according to D .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The left hand side of the formula gives the optimal performance that can be obtained by a deterministic algorithm A on a random input x (its average-case complexity), for a probability distribution D on inputs that is as hard as possible and with A being the algorithm that performs best against D .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The right hand side gives the optimal performance that can be obtained by a random algorithm R on a deterministic input x (its expected complexity), when R has the best performance on its worst case inputs, and when x is a worst case input to R .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The finiteness of ${\mathcal {A}}$ and ${\mathcal {X}}$ allows ${\mathcal {D}}$ and ${\mathcal {R}}$ to be interpreted as simplices of probability vectors, whose compactness implies that the minima and maxima in these formulas exist.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Another version of Yao's principle weakens it from an equality to an inequality, but at the same time generalizes it by relaxing the requirement that the algorithms and inputs come from a finite set.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The direction of the inequality allows it to be used when a specific input distribution has been shown to be hard for deterministic algorithms, converting it into a lower bound on the cost of all randomized algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] By avoiding maximization and minimization over ${\mathcal {D}}$ and ${\mathcal {R}}$ , this version of Yao's principle can apply in some cases where ${\mathcal {X}}$ or ${\mathcal {A}}$ are not finite.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Although this direction of inequality is the direction needed for proving lower bounds on randomized algorithms, the equality version of Yao's principle, when it is available, can also be useful in these proofs.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The equality of the principle implies that there is no loss of generality in using the principle to prove lower bounds: whatever the actual best randomized algorithm might be, there is some input distribution through which a matching lower bound on its complexity can be proven.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] When the cost c denotes the running time of an algorithm, Yao's principle states that the best possible running time of a deterministic algorithm, on a hard input distribution, gives a lower bound for the expected time of any Las Vegas algorithm on its worst-case input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Here, a Las Vegas algorithm is a randomized algorithm whose runtime may vary, but for which the result is always correct.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] For example, this form of Yao's principle has been used to prove the optimality of certain Monte Carlo tree search algorithms for the exact evaluation of game trees.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The time complexity of comparison-based sorting and selection algorithms is often studied using the number of comparisons between pairs of data elements as a proxy for the total time.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] When these problems are considered over a fixed set of elements, their inputs can be expressed as permutations and a deterministic algorithm can be expressed as a decision tree.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In this way both the inputs and the algorithms form finite sets as Yao's principle requires.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] A symmetrization argument identifies the hardest input distributions: They are the random permutations, the distributions on n distinct elements for which all permutations are equally likely.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] This is because, if any other distribution were hardest, averaging it with all permutations of the same hard distribution would be equally hard, and would produce the distribution for a random permutation.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle extends lower bounds for the average case number of comparisons made by deterministic algorithms, for random permutations, to the worst case analysis of randomized comparison algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] An example given by Yao is the analysis of algorithms for finding the k th largest of a given set of n values, the selection problem.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Subsequently, to Yao's work, Walter Cunto and Ian Munro showed that, for random permutations, any deterministic algorithm must perform at least $n+\min(k,n-k)-O(1)$ expected comparisons.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] By Yao's principle, the same number of comparisons must be made by randomized algorithms on their worst-case input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The Floyd–Rivest algorithm comes within $O({\sqrt {n\log n}})$ comparisons of this bound.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Another of the original applications by Yao of his principle was to the evasiveness of graph properties, the number of tests of the adjacency of pairs of vertices needed to determine whether a graph has a given property, when the only access to the graph is through such tests.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Karp conjectured that every randomized algorithm for every nontrivial monotone graph property (a property that remains true for every subgraph of a graph with the property) requires a quadratic number of tests, but only weaker bounds have been proven.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] As Yao stated, for graph properties that are true of the empty graph but false for some other graph on n vertices with only a bounded number s of edges, a randomized algorithm must probe a quadratic number of pairs of vertices.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] For instance, for the property of being a planar graph, $s=9$ because the 9-edge utility graph is non-planar.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] More precisely, Yao states that for these properties, at least $\left({\tfrac {1}{2}}-p\right){\tfrac {1}{s}}{\tbinom {n}{2}}$ tests are needed, for every $\varepsilon >0$ , for a randomized algorithm to have probability at most p of making a mistake.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao also used this method to show that quadratically many queries are needed for the properties of containing a given tree or clique as a subgraph, of containing a perfect matching, and of containing a Hamiltonian cycle, for small enough constant error probabilities.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In black-box optimization, the problem is to determine the minimum or maximum value of a function, from a given class of functions, accessible only through calls to the function on arguments from some finite domain.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In this case, the cost to be optimized is the number of calls.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle has been described as "the only method available for proving lower bounds for all randomized search heuristics for selected classes of problems".
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In communication complexity, an algorithm describes a communication protocol between two or more parties, and its cost may be the number of bits or messages transmitted between the parties.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In this case, Yao's principle describes an equality between the average-case complexity of deterministic communication protocols, on an input distribution that is the worst case for the problem, and the expected communication complexity of randomized protocols on their worst-case inputs.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] An example described by Avi Wigderson (based on a paper by Manu Viola) is the communication complexity for two parties, each holding n -bit input values, to determine which value is larger.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] For deterministic communication protocols, nothing better than n bits of communication is possible, easily achieved by one party sending their whole input to the other.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] However, parties with a shared source of randomness and a fixed error probability can exchange 1-bit hash functions of prefixes of the input to perform a noisy binary search for the first position where their inputs differ, achieving $O(\log n)$ bits of communication.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] This is within a constant factor of optimal, as can be shown via Yao's principle with an input distribution that chooses the position of the first difference uniformly at random, and then chooses random strings for the shared prefix up to that position and the rest of the inputs after that position.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle has also been applied to the competitive ratio of online algorithms.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] An online algorithm must respond to a sequence of requests, without knowledge of future requests, incurring some cost or profit per request depending on its choices.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The competitive ratio is the ratio of its cost or profit to the value that could be achieved by an *offline algorithm* with access to knowledge of all future requests, for a worst-case request sequence that causes this ratio to be as far from one as possible.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Here, one must be careful to formulate the ratio with the algorithm's performance in the numerator and the optimal performance of an offline algorithm in the denominator, so that the cost measure can be formulated as an expected value rather than as the reciprocal of an expected value.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] An example given by Borodin & El-Yaniv (2005) concerns page replacement algorithms, which respond to requests for pages of computer memory by using a cache of k pages, for a given parameter k .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] If a request matches a cached page, it costs nothing; otherwise one of the cached pages must be replaced by the requested page, at a cost of one page fault.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] A difficult distribution of request sequences for this model can be generated by choosing each request uniformly at random from a pool of $k+1$ pages.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Any deterministic online algorithm has ${\tfrac {n}{k+1}}$ expected page faults, over n requests.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Instead, an offline algorithm can divide the request sequence into phases within which only k pages are used, incurring only one fault at the start of a phase to replace the one page that is unused within the phase.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] As an instance of the coupon collector's problem, the expected requests per phase is $(k+1)H_{k}$ , where $H_{k}=1+{\tfrac {1}{2}}+\cdots +{\tfrac {1}{k}}$ is the k th harmonic number.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] By renewal theory, the offline algorithm incurs ${\tfrac {n}{(k+1)H_{k}}}+o(n)$ page faults with high probability, so the competitive ratio of any deterministic algorithm against this input distribution is at least $H_{k}$ .
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] By Yao's principle, $H_{k}$ also lower bounds the competitive ratio of any randomized page replacement algorithm against a request sequence chosen by an *oblivious adversary* to be a worst case for the algorithm but without knowledge of the algorithm's random choices.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] For online problems in a general class related to the ski rental problem, Seiden has proposed a cookbook method for deriving optimally hard input distributions, based on certain parameters of the problem.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's principle may be interpreted in game theoretic terms, via a two-player zero-sum game in which one player, Alice, selects a deterministic algorithm, the other player, Bob, selects an input, and the payoff is the cost of the selected algorithm on the selected input.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Any randomized algorithm R may be interpreted as a randomized choice among deterministic algorithms, and thus as a mixed strategy for Alice.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Similarly, a non-random algorithm may be thought of as a pure strategy for Alice.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In any two-player zero-sum game, if one player chooses a mixed strategy, then the other player has an optimal pure strategy against it.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Thus, the minimax mixed strategy for Alice, set against the best opposing pure strategy for Bob, produces the same expected game value c as the minimax mixed strategy for Bob, set against the best opposing pure strategy for Alice.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] This equality of expected game values, for the game described above, is Yao's principle in its form as an equality.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Yao's 1977 paper, originally formulating Yao's principle, proved it in this way.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The optimal mixed strategy for Alice (a randomized algorithm) and the optimal mixed strategy for Bob (a hard input distribution) may each be computed using a linear program that has one player's probabilities as its variables, with a constraint on the game value for each choice of the other player.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The two linear programs obtained in this way for each player are dual linear programs, whose equality is an instance of linear programming duality.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] However, although linear programs may be solved in polynomial time, the numbers of variables and constraints in these linear programs (numbers of possible algorithms and inputs) are typically too large to list explicitly.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Therefore, formulating and solving these programs to find these optimal strategies is often impractical.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] For Monte Carlo algorithms, algorithms that use a fixed amount of computational resources but that may produce an erroneous result, a form of Yao's principle applies to the probability of an error, the error rate of an algorithm.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Choosing the hardest possible input distribution, and the algorithm that achieves the lowest error rate against that distribution, gives the same error rate as choosing an optimal algorithm and its worst case input distribution.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] However, the hard input distributions found in this way are not robust to changes in the parameters used when applying this principle.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] If an input distribution requires high complexity to achieve a certain error rate, it may nevertheless have unexpectedly low complexity for a different error rate.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Ben-David and Blais show that, for Boolean functions under many natural measures of computational complexity, there exists an input distribution that is simultaneously hard for all error rates.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] Variants of Yao's principle have also been considered for quantum computing.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] In place of randomized algorithms, one may consider quantum algorithms that have a good probability of computing the correct value for every input (probability at least ${\tfrac {2}{3}}$ ); this condition together with polynomial time defines the complexity class BQP.
[src:randomized-algorithms-deep/yao-s-principle] The weak form of this inequality is within a constant factor of being an equality, but the strong form is not.
